        "id": 253470,
        "name": "",
        "username": "vegaldn",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/vegaldn/{size}/49147_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-10-12T20:43:10.467Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I have a question regarding your policy on storing messages on servers. I understand that Signal uses end-to-end encryption to protect user data, and that even if messages are temporarily stored on the server, they remain encrypted. However, I would like to better understand the specific risks associated with storing encrypted messages on the server, even if the encryption keys remain with the clients.</p>\n<p>Why does Signal choose to delete messages from the servers after delivery instead of storing them encrypted? What is the privacy risk if messages remain encrypted and the keys are never sent to the server?</p>\n<p><strong>How does Signal send messages to all synced devices at once?</strong> For example, user A sends a message to user B, and how does the server distribute the messages to all devices? What mechanism does it use to do this?</p>\n<p><strong>How does syncing work in Signal?</strong> Since messages are not stored on the server, where does the new device get them from?</p>\n<p>Thanks</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 5,
        "updated_at": "2024-10-12T20:43:10.467Z",
